[7] Canada (Alberta)
Date: Tue 28 Jan 2014
Source: The Calgary Sun [edited]
http://www.calgarysun.com/2014/01/28/measles-case-at-childrens-hospital--alberta-health-services-sends-letters-warning-of-potential-exposure


Three visits to the Alberta Children's Hospital emergency room by a child with measles earlier this month [January 2014] has left other patients at those times at risk, Alberta Health Services [AHS] said.

AHS has sent out letters warning those who might have been exposed to the disease. Those who were in the ER on 14 Jan 2014 from 1:30-8:34 p.m., 16 Jan 2014 from 6 p.m. to 17 Jan 2014 at 1:53 a.m. and 18 Jan 2014 from 12:41-9:18 p.m. will receive the AHS letter. "Only those who have received a letter from Alberta Health Services have potentially been exposed to measles," said Dr. Judy MacDonald, medical officer of health for Alberta Health Services in Calgary. "There is not a risk to the general public."

The incident at Alberta Children's Hospital follows a Saskatchewan measles case passing through Calgary by plane on 7 Jan 2014, and a student at Western Canada High School confirmed as having the disease on 10 Jan 2014. The previous incidents both involved travel to the Philippines. AHS advises calling Health Link Alberta at 1-866-408-5465 if symptoms develop rather than attending a health care facility.

Health Link Alberta lists symptoms as including fever, cough, acute nasal mucous membrane discharge, inflammation of the lining of the eyelids, a spreading rash, and eruption of small, irregular, bright red spots on the inner cheeks in the mouth with a minute bluish or white speck in the centre of each.

[Byline: Damien Weed]

