[8] Canada (Saskatchewan)
Date: Fri 31 Jan 2014
Source: Leader Post [edited]
http://www.leaderpost.com/health/Sask+health+officials+watching+cases+measles/9454684/story.html


There is one new confirmed cases of measles in the province, bringing the total to 6. The latest case of measles was confirmed on Friday [31 Jan 2014] by the Ministry of Health.

Five of the 6 cases of measles have been reported in the Regina Qu'Appelle Health Region. "There is follow up of rash illness in terms of people who may have been exposed to the various public settings," Dr. Denise Werker, the province's deputy chief medical health officer, told reporters on Friday [31 Jan 2014] morning. The incubation period -- from when someone is exposed to measles to the onset of symptoms -- is about 3 weeks. "We're looking at the 1st block of 21 days and seeing if there are going to be new cases," Werker said. "We're just waiting and watching and putting in measures in case there are additional cases."

The Saskatchewan Health Ministry issued a special public alert about the potentially deadly disease on 17 Jan 2014 after it received confirmation of measles in an unimmunized infant who travelled by air to Saskatchewan in early January 2014. The ministry issued the alert because measles is a highly infectious and potentially serious disease that is easily transmitted through the air. Symptoms include high fever, cough and runny nose, followed by a rash. The rash often starts on the face before spreading to the rest of the body. Measles vaccination is usually offered in combination with mumps and rubella in one vaccine at 12 months and again at 18 months. Most people born before 1970 are considered to be immune to the disease, but those born after 1970 should get 2 shots of the MMR vaccine.

People who suspect they have measles should phone their physician or health-care provider in advance so arrangements can be made for them to be examined and get lab tests.

[Byline: Pamela Cowan]

