[9] Australia (New South Wales)
Date: Thu 30 Jan 2014
Source: Northern Star [edited]
http://www.northernstar.com.au/news/protect-yourself-from-measles-outbreak/2154440/


North Coast health officials have warned people travelling to the Philippines to ensure they are immunised against measles because of the ongoing measles outbreak in that country. Greg Bell, North Coast deputy director of public health, said measles was highly contagious among people who were not fully immunised. "Measles is spread through coughing and sneezing and is one of the most contagious infections known," he said. "Complications can range from swelling of the brain and pneumonia to ear infections and diarrhoea. In recent weeks, there have been 10 cases of measles reported in NSW (New South Wales). Seven were associated with travel to the Philippines, including 3 young children who were admitted to hospital. NSW Health urges everyone planning on travelling to the Philippines to ensure they are up to date with their vaccinations before they travel."

